}

{
    "analysis": "Metric-level anomaly scan for the five candidate services (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service) has been performed. Results show multiple KPI series in at least three services exceeded their global P95 during the incident window. Notably: ts-order-service and ts-route-service have anomaly timestamps around 09:56–10:00 UTC (earliest anomalies ~09:56–09:57 and 10:00), while ts-auth-service anomalies appear later (~10:08–10:14 UTC). Each listed (service, KPI) has a small number of exceedances (count=2 in the summary), so faults appear as short consecutive breaches. This ordering suggests ts-order-service and ts-route-service issues started earlier in the window and could be upstream causes; ts-auth-service deviations occur later and might be either downstream impact or a separate fault. To decide which service is the root cause we must inspect traces to see call chains and which faulty service is the most downstream faulty service in those traces. Trace-level anomaly detection (using full-series global thresholds then filtering to incident window) is the next logical step to localize the root-cause service in the call graph.",
