{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric-level and trace-level anomaly detection for the five candidate services. Metric analysis shows ts-order-service had the most severe relative breach (latency-90 at 09:56 UTC with ~765% breach) and several other KPI breaches (cpu, diskio, socket, workload) early in the incident window. ts-route-service and ts-auth-service also show anomalies but start later (ts-route ~10:00 UTC, ts-auth ~10:10–10:15 UTC). Trace aggregation indicates ts-order-service observed anomalous traces involving peers such as ts-travel-service, ts-seat-service, ts-preserve-service, and self-root traces beginning at 09:56–09:59 UTC. According to the diagnosis rules, when multiple service-level faults exist, the root cause is usually the most downstream faulty service in the trace call chain. We still need to reconstruct call directions among the faulty services to find the most-downstream faulty service: specifically, inspect the anomalous trace names for ts-order-service, ts-route-service, and ts-auth-service to identify 'from' vs 'to' relationships and earliest anomaly times per pair. This will let us see whether ts-order-service is upstream or downstream of other faulty services and therefore whether it is the root cause. We have not yet inspected logs; but logs may be secondary once the root service is localized. ",
