    "instruction": "For log.csv: compute global P95 and P5 per (cmdb_id, log_name) using the full available series. Then filter log rows to the incident window 2024-01-22 09:53:25 UTC to 2024-01-22 10:23:25 UTC. For cmdb_id == 'ts-order-service' only, report each log_name where any in-window points exceed the global P95 or fall below the global P5. Return a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, count_total_in_window, count_points_above_global_P95_in_window, count_points_below_global_P5_in_window, earliest_timestamp_of_anomaly_in_window (UTC), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5. Limit to up to 20 rows. If no such log anomalies are found for ts-order-service, return an explicit empty indication."}

Summary of findings (concise):
- Earliest and most significant anomaly observed at 2024-01-22 09:56:00 UTC: ts-order-service showed a huge relative spike in latency (latency-90 ~765% above global P95), and many callers recorded increased durations when calling ts-order-service starting at the same time.
- ts-order-service also had anomalous log.row_count behavior (spikes and drops) inside the window; ts-auth-service anomalies occurred later (~10:10–10:15 UTC), consistent with downstream impact.
- Resource KPIs on ts-order-service (CPU/memory/disk) only showed modest breaches; the dominant symptom is high response latency at ts-order-service.

